[1
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 01:58:16 EST
From: Peter Cyrog <Drzero@aol.com>

What about influenza viruses? There is a known mutation/transmission route
of duck-pig-human for new strains of flu viruses? Are we opening the
possibility of another pandemic a la 1918? And I assume it is well
documented that immunosuppressed people are susceptible to normally
innocuous organisms. I have seen a reference for an immunosuppressed person
catching _Bordetella bronchiseptica_ (Canine Infectious Tracheobronchitis
aka Kennel Cough)from their dog. Isn't something of this order possible
from transplanted organs?
Are donors (i.e. Pigs) checked for diseases or are they raised as germ free
animals as transplant sources? Can pigs be raised virus free?
--
Peter Cyrog, DVM
Los Angeles, Calif. USA
e-mail: Drzero@aol.com
[To quote Marie Cornu of (02) of this thread: "Only gnotobiotic (or axenic)
pigs, which would have grown in perfectly sterile conditions, could be
candidates for xenotransplantation. So, the risk of pathogens inhabiting
pig's tissue would be therefore very limited, as long as it concerns
microorganisms." Now read on. - Mod.MHJ
