[2
Date: Tue, 24 Nov 1998 09:00:52 +0100
From: John-Erik Stig Hansen <jesh@dadlnet.dk>

Expression of the Gal(a1-3)Gal epitope in tissues from non-human mammals
like the pig is responsible for the hyperacute rejection of xenotransplants
where preformed Gal(a1-3)Gal antibodies in human serum react with the
endothelium of transplanted organs (Bach FH et al. Nature Med 1:869-873,
1995).
In recent years much effort has been spent on creating transgenic pigs and
other potential donor animals where the Gal(a1-3)Gal epitope is not exposed
and where hyperacute rejection would not take place. This, however, would
also break down the defensive barrier which protects humans against viruses
endogenous in the donor species, because such viruses would no longer be
immediately recognized by preformed antibodies in human serum (Patience C
et al. Nature Med 3:282-286, 1997).
Concern has therefore been raised that endogenous retroviruses foreign to
the human species would be allowed inside our evolutionally developed
defence and could act as Trojan horses with potentially devastating
consequences not only to recipients of a xenotransplant but also to the
population as a whole (Weiss R. Nature 391:327-328, 1998).
--
John-Erik Stig Hansen, M.D., D.Sc.
